<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1896-03-30T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1896-03-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="766" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d766">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Williams</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Rockhill</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">United
                                        States Consulate-General</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Habana</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1896-03-30"><hi rend="italic">March 30,
                                1896</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 2847.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to report to the
                            Department, on information received from Mr. Viondi, the advocate, that
                            the military court having under its investigation the charges against
                            Mr. Julio Sanguily and some twenty others for participation in the
                            kidnaping of Mr. Antonio Fernandez de Castro by the bandit Manuel Garcia
                            on his plantation near the towns of Bainoa and Aguacate in the year
                            1894, has quashed all these cases. They are still pending, however,
                            before the civil court.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Ramon O. Williams</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Consul-General.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>